We investigate the anomalous transport of passive tracers advected by a three-dimensional, quenched velocity field generated by a static configuration of vortex filaments. Using numerical simulations, we analyze tracer trajectories for systems with filament densities ranging from $N=5$ to $N=40$ to characterize the transport regime. Our analysis focuses on the scaling of the mean squared displacement (MSD), the statistical properties of the velocity probability density function (PDF), the velocity autocorrelation function (VACF), and the local flow topology via the Okubo-Weiss criterion. We find that the transport is strongly superdiffusive, with the anomalous exponent $\alpha$ decreasing from nearly ballistic values ($\alpha \approx 1.99$) at low filament densities towards the theoretical Holtsmark prediction at the highest density studied ($N=40$, $\alpha \approx 1.84$), though the asymptotic limit is not reached within our simulation parameters. The tails of the empirical velocity PDF are consistent with the heavy-tailed Holtsmark distribution predicted for velocity fields with a $1/r^2$ spatial decay. Analysis of the velocity autocorrelation function reveals persistent correlations and anti-correlations distinct from a renewal L\'evy walk process, while the Okubo-Weiss analysis demonstrates that low-speed events are spatially correlated with rotation-dominated regions of the flow. Significant variability among individual tracer trajectories underscores the non-ergodic nature of transport in the quenched disorder.

